{{see|Ken}}

==English==

===Etymology===
Northern dialect and {{sco}} from {{ang}} ''[[cennan]]'' "make known, declare, acknowledge," originally "make to know," causative of ''[[cunnan]]'' "to become acquainted with, to know". The noun meaning "range of sight" is a nautical abbreviation of present participle [[kenning]].

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# [[knowledge|Knowledge]] or [[perception]].
# {{nautical}} Range of sight.

===Verb===
[[Category:English irregular verbs]]
'''to ken''' ('''[[kens]]''', '''[[kenning]]''', '''[[kenned]]''' or '''[[kent]]''', '''[[kenned]]''' or '''[[kent]]''')
#{{transitive}} To [[know]], [[perceive]] or [[understand]].
#:''Do ye '''ken''' John Peel with his coat so gay?'' - 18th century ballad

====Related terms====
*[[kenned]]
*[[kenning]]

====References====
* '''1987''' ''The New Geordie Dictionary'' ISBN 0946928118

